<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="30" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
There are several type specimens of species described by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mellié">Mellie</normalizedToken>
deposited in historical collections of the MHNG and the MNHN. In the MHNG, these types are in the A. Melly collection, who has a surname similar to that of J. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mellié">Mellie</normalizedToken>
but shall not be confounded. We did not find type material of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
in the Chevrolat collection of MNHN. We located a female specimen from Colombia in the Melly collection of MHNG named as 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mellie, J" journalOrPublisher="Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France" pageId="15" pageNumber="38" pagination="205 - 274" title="Monographie de l'ancien genre Cis des auteurs." volume="6" year="1849">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mellié">Mellie</normalizedToken>
(1849)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned he has examined specimens from both the Chevrolat and the Melly collections, therefore there is a possibility that this single specimen we located in the Melly collection is a syntype, but we cannot assure this. We compared this female with female paralectotypes of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus corpulentus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corpulentus">Xylographus corpulentus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus lemoulti" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lemoulti">Xylographus lemoulti</taxonomicName>
and they are exactly the same. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mellie, J" journalOrPublisher="Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France" pageId="15" pageNumber="38" pagination="205 - 274" title="Monographie de l'ancien genre Cis des auteurs." volume="6" year="1849">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mellié">Mellie</normalizedToken>
(1849)
</bibRefCitation>
provided few differences between 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus corpulentus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corpulentus">Xylographus corpulentus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
, stating that they resemble each other &quot;pour la taille et la forme&quot;, with 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
being more punctate. We believe the description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
was based on a female specimen, because the pronotal surface between punctures is described as being finely rugose. We have observed that it is common in female 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Xylographus</taxonomicName>
species to have pronotal surface distinctly more rugose than that of males. The type of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus corpulentus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corpulentus">Xylographus corpulentus</taxonomicName>
was described as being black, while the one of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
was described as reddish. It is a common variation found in 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus corpulentus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corpulentus">Xylographus corpulentus</taxonomicName>
, in which teneral adults may be reddish (pers. obs.). 
<bibRefCitation author="Pic, M" journalOrPublisher="Moulins" pageId="15" pageNumber="38" pagination="1 - 20" title="Diagnoses generiques et specifiques." volumeTitle="Melanges Exotico-entomologiques" year="1916 b">Pic (1916b)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus lemoulti" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lemoulti">Xylographus lemoulti</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
in the coloration and pronotal shape, again a consequence of the fact that the description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mellie, 1847" authorityName="Mellie" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Xylographus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylographus richardi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">Xylographus richardi</taxonomicName>
was based in a teneral adult female. The type-localities of 
